```typescript
export function nextGeneration(liveCells: [number, number][]): [number, number][] {
  const liveSet = new Set(liveCells.map(([x, y]) => `${x},${y}`));

  const candidates = new Map<string, number>();
  for (const [x, y] of liveCells) {
    for (let dx = -1; dx <= 1; dx++) {
      for (let dy = -1; dy <= 1; dy++) {
        if (dx === 0 && dy === 0) continue;
        const key = `${x + dx},${y + dy}`;
        candidates.set(key, (candidates.get(key) || 0) + 1);
      }
    }
  }

  const result: [number, number][] = [];
  for (const [key, count] of candidates) {
    const isAlive = liveSet.has(key);
    if (isAlive && (count === 2 || count === 3)) {
      const [x, y] = key.split(",").map(Number);
      result.push([x, y]);
    } else if (!isAlive && count === 3) {
      const [x, y] = key.split(",").map(Number);
      result.push([x, y]);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

Review for Simple Design Rules and APP. I see one duplication: the `key.split(",").map(Number)` and `result.push` lines are duplicated in the two branches. The condition can be simplified: a cell lives if (alive AND 2-3 neighbors) OR (dead AND 3 neighbors), which simplifies to: count === 3 OR (count === 2 AND alive).

Apply refactoring if warranted. Run `pnpm test` to confirm tests still pass.

